WEBVTT

00:14.014 --> 00:15.556
That's a big mountain.

00:15.557 --> 00:16.807
The map is clear.

00:16.808 --> 00:20.352
The Reverse Mountain waterway is
our best option to enter the Grand Line.

00:20.353 --> 00:21.729
Then let's do it.

00:21.730 --> 00:23.313
I don't know about navigation,

00:23.314 --> 00:25.774
but I do know
a ship can't travel up a mountain.

00:25.775 --> 00:28.278
Nami knows how it works.
That's good enough for me.

00:30.572 --> 00:33.615
Well, I have a theory on how it works.

00:33.616 --> 00:36.493
The currents of the four seas
should drive us up.

00:36.494 --> 00:38.871
However, the waters here are colder,

00:38.872 --> 00:41.999
so the currents at the mountain's edge
travel down to the sea floor.

00:42.000 --> 00:44.043
Meaning if we don't hit it just right,

00:44.044 --> 00:46.754
we could crash and be dragged
to the bottom of the ocean.

00:46.755 --> 00:47.756
Wha…

00:48.798 --> 00:50.090
It's very technical.

00:50.091 --> 00:51.842
Get it right or die.

00:51.843 --> 00:53.552
Okay, not that technical.

00:53.553 --> 00:55.763
Look, the Red Line circles the world.

00:55.764 --> 00:58.223
We can't go around it.
We have to go through it.

00:58.224 --> 01:01.061
If our navigator says
this is how we get to the Grand Line,

01:02.395 --> 01:04.522
then this is how we get to the Grand Line.

01:05.065 --> 01:05.899
Hmm?

01:31.716 --> 01:33.342
That's a lot of shipwrecks.

01:33.343 --> 01:37.097
See? Not everyone ends up
on the bottom of the ocean.

01:40.058 --> 01:41.851
Just keep us steady, Usopp.

01:47.273 --> 01:49.109
Go easy on the whipstaff.

01:54.322 --> 01:56.324
Usopp, hard to port!

02:06.417 --> 02:07.877
Okay, that wasn't so

02:08.378 --> 02:09.712
bad.

02:23.268 --> 02:24.686
Everyone, hang on!

02:28.940 --> 02:30.275
Whoa!

02:34.487 --> 02:35.696
Yeah!

02:35.697 --> 02:39.075
Nami! The Merry's fighting me!

02:39.784 --> 02:41.411
Whoa!

02:44.622 --> 02:47.207
Usopp, we're gonna hit those rocks!
Go port!

02:47.208 --> 02:49.419
I can't! The current's too strong!

02:58.428 --> 03:00.305
Aah! Oh!

03:04.142 --> 03:05.435
Stay with it!

03:07.103 --> 03:08.313
Keep fighting the current!

03:10.899 --> 03:13.193
Come on, Merry, work with me.

03:25.205 --> 03:27.081
Don't push it too hard, or it's gonna…

03:27.999 --> 03:29.709
- No!
- Break.

03:30.752 --> 03:32.337
How do we steer now?

03:50.772 --> 03:51.773
Brace for impact!

03:52.899 --> 03:53.900
Aah!

04:14.629 --> 04:15.755
We're saved!

04:16.256 --> 04:17.966
We're not out of this yet!

04:20.009 --> 04:22.637
Set the mizzen. I'm going forward.

04:23.304 --> 04:24.639
I got you!

05:02.385 --> 05:04.846
- Whoo!
- We're reaching the peak!

05:06.806 --> 05:09.391
Woo-hoo!

05:09.392 --> 05:12.645
Yeah! This! This is a ride!

05:14.439 --> 05:16.106
Prepare to sheet in.

05:16.107 --> 05:17.650
Hard to starboard!

05:24.907 --> 05:26.825
Yeah! Come on!

05:26.826 --> 05:28.244
Come on, Merry!

05:36.419 --> 05:37.462
Sheet in!

06:01.861 --> 06:02.945
We did it!

06:04.614 --> 06:05.948
It's the Grand Line!

06:12.914 --> 06:14.957
Now all we have to do is go down.

06:19.670 --> 06:20.755
Full speed ahead.

06:22.715 --> 06:23.716
Aah!

06:29.806 --> 06:31.265
Oh!

06:37.438 --> 06:38.606
Whoa!

06:39.690 --> 06:42.193
Whoo!

06:53.371 --> 06:55.498
Whoo! Whoo!

06:56.833 --> 06:59.001
Whoo!

07:08.386 --> 07:09.470
What's that?

07:14.267 --> 07:17.186
Whatever it is, we're gonna hit it!

07:25.319 --> 07:26.946
Hey, whale!

07:28.030 --> 07:29.657
Get out of the way!

07:34.162 --> 07:36.247
- Luffy, no!
- Luffy!

08:03.566 --> 08:06.027
Five more minutes, Dadan.

08:30.843 --> 08:31.844
Hey, you!

08:33.179 --> 08:34.931
Whoa.

08:36.641 --> 08:37.892
Stop that!

08:38.935 --> 08:40.770
Give me back my crew!

08:46.484 --> 08:48.653
Okay, you want it the tough way?

08:49.320 --> 08:51.781
Be my guest, fish!

08:59.580 --> 09:01.332
You jerk!

09:02.208 --> 09:05.085
Stop being a coward and come closer!

09:05.086 --> 09:06.504
Come on!

09:07.755 --> 09:08.756
If I…

09:10.758 --> 09:14.303
If I could swim,
you'd be in so much trouble right now.

09:15.638 --> 09:19.267
You're gonna need
something a lot bigger than your fists.

09:23.312 --> 09:24.563
Who are you?

09:24.564 --> 09:26.065
Just an old man

09:26.899 --> 09:29.735
doing his job.

09:30.570 --> 09:33.823
All right, you overgrown guppy.

10:00.766 --> 10:01.767
Oh.

10:02.393 --> 10:03.311
Whoa.

10:03.853 --> 10:07.105
Um… hey, my friends are still in there.

10:07.106 --> 10:09.609
We have to get them out of there now!

10:10.401 --> 10:12.820
Your friends are dead.

10:22.788 --> 10:24.790
I need to get my friends
out of that whale.

10:27.668 --> 10:30.838
I'm not leaving until I get some answers.
Who are you?

10:31.464 --> 10:34.924
What's the deal with the whale?
How do I get them out?

10:34.925 --> 10:36.968
You want some answers? Here we go.

10:36.969 --> 10:40.764
Name's Crocus.
Occupation? Lighthouse keeper.

10:40.765 --> 10:42.308
71 years old.

10:42.808 --> 10:44.560
Gemini. Type AB blood.

10:45.394 --> 10:49.856
That deluded whale is trying to break
through the Red Line, which is impossible.

10:49.857 --> 10:51.651
As for your crew,

10:52.151 --> 10:53.944
it's useless.

10:54.820 --> 10:56.197
I already told you.

10:57.156 --> 10:59.408
Your crew is dead.

11:00.368 --> 11:01.869
You don't know my crew.

11:24.975 --> 11:26.936
Your map say anything about a giant whale?

11:27.520 --> 11:30.356
- Obviously not.
- Do we think Luffy's okay?

11:32.024 --> 11:33.358
Of course.

11:33.359 --> 11:36.195
It's Luffy. He's… durable.

11:36.946 --> 11:41.074
- We need to find a way out of here.
- Why don't you let me come up with a plan?

11:41.075 --> 11:43.326
I didn't know
the whale was gonna be there, okay?

11:43.327 --> 11:46.706
At least <i>I</i> didn't break the whipstaff
with my giant muscles.

11:47.206 --> 11:48.331
Not a compliment.

11:48.332 --> 11:50.126
Not <i>not</i> a compliment.

11:50.835 --> 11:53.753
Okay. Usopp, you know
how to fix the Merry, right?

11:53.754 --> 11:57.800
Of course. But the tiller's useless
without a new rowle, so…

11:58.551 --> 12:00.845
- You think you can find one out there?
- Out there?

12:02.430 --> 12:05.014
On those perilous wrecks?

12:05.015 --> 12:06.808
Perilous and most likely haunted.

12:06.809 --> 12:08.269
Sounds like it's a two-man job.

12:09.270 --> 12:12.397
While they're gone, I will work out a plan
to get us out of here.

12:12.398 --> 12:13.898
I'll handle it.

12:13.899 --> 12:16.026
A sword isn't gonna get us out of a whale.

12:19.363 --> 12:20.698
We'll see about that.

12:24.326 --> 12:26.494
Did you call ahead
and prep the Billower Bike?

12:26.495 --> 12:27.412
Yes, Captain.

12:27.413 --> 12:29.831
Um, but the Grand Line's
out of our jurisdiction,

12:29.832 --> 12:32.792
so we'll need to make a formal petition
for reassignment to our superiors--

12:32.793 --> 12:35.837
Here's my petition. I don't care.
Why don't you tell him that?

12:35.838 --> 12:38.716
Why don't you tell me yourself, Captain?

12:41.719 --> 12:44.679
Vice Admiral Garp.
Uh, welcome to Loguetown.

12:44.680 --> 12:46.891
What's a bigwig like you
doing round these parts?

12:47.725 --> 12:49.351
Celebrate the anniversary?

12:52.188 --> 12:55.733
Headed back to Marineford Headquarters,
but thought I'd, um…

12:56.275 --> 12:59.987
I thought I'd stop by
and check up on things.

13:01.405 --> 13:04.115
I have a matter to discuss with you.

13:04.116 --> 13:08.204
Plus, it'll give my new protégés
a chance to expand their horizons.

13:08.829 --> 13:10.830
It's about time we got off that boat.

13:10.831 --> 13:12.624
- Helmeppo, quiet.
- What?

13:12.625 --> 13:16.211
You've literally passed out or thrown up
more than I have during training.

13:16.212 --> 13:18.046
And we deserve some shore leave.

13:18.047 --> 13:19.632
Are you feeding strays now?

13:20.382 --> 13:23.176
Trainee pools must not be what they were.

13:23.177 --> 13:26.096
You weren't exactly a model recruit
when you started.

13:27.306 --> 13:28.641
I think they'd surprise you.

13:29.558 --> 13:31.977
Walk around town, lads.
You might learn something.

13:32.770 --> 13:35.355
I'm gonna have a word
with the esteemed captain here.

13:35.356 --> 13:39.108
Sir… might we learn more
by shadowing you in your meeting?

13:39.109 --> 13:40.527
In private.

13:40.528 --> 13:43.321
If you don't want to explore,
you can return to the ship.

13:43.322 --> 13:47.701
I hear Bogard has creative ideas
for new ways to do push-ups.

13:48.285 --> 13:50.870
Tashigi will show them around.

13:50.871 --> 13:52.081
Perfect.

13:53.082 --> 13:54.458
Lead the way, Captain.

13:54.959 --> 13:56.252
This way, sir.

14:07.596 --> 14:08.597
Hi.

14:11.517 --> 14:12.351
Hmm.

14:19.233 --> 14:21.901
Flower guy, I need your help!

14:21.902 --> 14:24.405
Grandpa, open up!

14:26.490 --> 14:28.534
I need to save my friends from this whale!

14:30.077 --> 14:31.954
I know you can open the door!

14:32.746 --> 14:34.456
Flower Pops, I need your help!

14:35.875 --> 14:37.334
Open the door!

14:39.336 --> 14:40.796
Open up!

14:59.940 --> 15:01.859
Peace at last.

15:11.702 --> 15:16.164
Have you any idea how hard it is
to get a door repairman out here?

15:16.165 --> 15:19.167
My friends and I made a promise
to journey across the Grand Line

15:19.168 --> 15:20.961
and achieve our dreams.

15:21.587 --> 15:23.589
I'm not setting sail without them.

15:24.798 --> 15:28.093
Doesn't matter what I have to do
to get them out of that whale,

15:29.553 --> 15:31.013
because nothing…

15:31.972 --> 15:36.518
nothing gets in the way
of Monkey D. Luffy and his crew!

15:38.395 --> 15:41.523
You're not going to give up, are you?

15:43.567 --> 15:44.401
Nope.

15:50.991 --> 15:54.452
There's only one way
to approach Laboon safely

15:54.453 --> 15:56.872
and see if your friends
are alive in there.

15:57.623 --> 15:58.624
- Laboon?
- Mmm.

16:00.668 --> 16:03.671
- You named the whale?
- No! He came with it.

16:04.588 --> 16:05.422
Ah.

16:06.173 --> 16:07.466
Thanks for the help.

16:12.179 --> 16:13.764
You remind me of someone.

16:14.765 --> 16:16.475
He couldn't shut up either.

16:29.613 --> 16:32.157
How many of those
do you get through in a week?

16:35.327 --> 16:36.704
Depends on the week.

16:39.707 --> 16:41.166
And what a week it's been.

16:41.959 --> 16:47.171
A rare dark mark
on the sterling record of Captain Smoker.

16:47.172 --> 16:48.007
Hmm.

16:52.428 --> 16:53.887
So serious.

16:55.139 --> 16:57.766
You remind me of myself
when I was your age.

16:59.518 --> 17:02.395
I didn't become a Marine
just to add notches to my belt.

17:02.396 --> 17:03.939
Still…

17:04.773 --> 17:06.942
…hurts to watch one sail away.

17:07.443 --> 17:08.861
You would know.

17:14.366 --> 17:17.785
I have intel that the Straw Hats
are heading to find the One Piece

17:17.786 --> 17:19.747
to answer Gold Roger's call.

17:20.330 --> 17:21.790
They're not the first.

17:22.708 --> 17:24.168
Won't be the last.

17:27.004 --> 17:28.047
I'm going after him.

17:30.841 --> 17:32.216
Because he escaped you?

17:32.217 --> 17:34.719
Because he's trying to finish
what Gold Roger started.

17:34.720 --> 17:37.013
Are you comparing Luffy to Roger?

17:37.014 --> 17:38.598
You weren't there.

17:38.599 --> 17:40.850
You didn't see how he smiled
in the face of death.

17:40.851 --> 17:42.269
Just like Gold Roger did.

17:42.936 --> 17:44.771
I need to stop him

17:44.772 --> 17:46.565
by any means necessary.

17:50.152 --> 17:52.320
I understand you want
to protect your grandson.

17:52.321 --> 17:53.947
You understand nothing.

17:56.533 --> 17:59.495
I've given up trying to protect Luffy.

18:03.874 --> 18:08.587
Pirates can't navigate through
the Calm Belt the way Marine vessels can.

18:10.547 --> 18:14.802
Their only option to enter the Grand Line
is through Reverse Mountain.

18:15.385 --> 18:19.306
Chances are they won't survive the voyage.

18:20.182 --> 18:21.850
Why waste your time?

18:22.684 --> 18:25.687
Wasting my time would be
sitting on my ass doing nothing.

18:27.940 --> 18:28.774
Respectfully.

18:29.525 --> 18:32.151
Your request, if you can call it that,

18:32.152 --> 18:33.444
is denied.

18:33.445 --> 18:36.239
- Sir--
- Your skill set's needed elsewhere.

18:36.240 --> 18:42.162
The Straw Hats are a speck of dust
in the gears of the Grand Line.

18:44.456 --> 18:46.541
The Marines are concerned

18:46.542 --> 18:50.086
with real threats
to our delicate political ecosystem.

18:50.087 --> 18:53.464
The Kingdom of Alabasta
is on the verge of civil war,

18:53.465 --> 18:55.424
and their princess is still missing,

18:55.425 --> 18:57.260
possibly abducted.

18:57.261 --> 19:02.306
Meanwhile, the Revolutionary Army
gains supporters every day

19:02.307 --> 19:05.310
in its quest
to overturn the World Government.

19:07.354 --> 19:08.604
And their leader--

19:08.605 --> 19:10.023
Was in Loguetown.

19:11.024 --> 19:11.984
Dragon.

19:13.735 --> 19:15.821
He aided the Straw Hats in their escape.

19:16.405 --> 19:17.364
Did he now?

19:28.876 --> 19:30.544
If you want to do your duty,

19:31.879 --> 19:34.798
I'll show you
what a real threat looks like.

19:42.598 --> 19:43.515
Oh.

19:44.474 --> 19:45.475
Ugh.

19:54.902 --> 19:55.736
That's not water.

19:57.070 --> 19:58.238
Stomach acid.

20:00.866 --> 20:03.118
Strong enough to slowly erode these ships.

20:03.702 --> 20:06.038
Probably does
an even quicker job on flesh.

20:06.997 --> 20:09.541
I wonder how long
before the Merry starts to erode.

20:10.125 --> 20:11.335
Let's not find out.

20:17.966 --> 20:21.136
Do you know ghosts that haunt shipwrecks
are the most vengeful?

20:22.596 --> 20:23.555
Yeah, right.

20:24.640 --> 20:26.807
Where'd you hear that? Was it in a book?

20:26.808 --> 20:28.936
Who wrote the book?
Was it well researched?

20:30.020 --> 20:32.104
What is a rowle, by the way?

20:32.105 --> 20:34.690
It's where the whipstaff
connects to the tiller.

20:34.691 --> 20:36.693
No tiller, no rudder, no way to steer.

20:39.363 --> 20:41.823
Well, you can never be prepared
for the unknown, buddy.

20:42.324 --> 20:44.367
You seem pretty unbothered by that.

20:44.368 --> 20:48.247
See, in a kitchen,
you never know what's gonna come at you.

20:48.747 --> 20:52.042
But… just keep your head down,

20:52.793 --> 20:55.127
trust your own hands on the tools,

20:55.128 --> 20:57.547
trust that your crew will have your back…

21:00.300 --> 21:03.303
and then you'll feel
like you can handle anything.

21:04.221 --> 21:07.181
That's actually… kind of inspiring.

21:07.182 --> 21:10.560
With trust like that,
you'll never be afraid.

21:17.734 --> 21:19.027
Startled.

21:19.820 --> 21:20.904
Not afraid.

21:21.822 --> 21:22.698
Not judging.

21:25.325 --> 21:27.995
Ugh, he's not even been dead long.
He's still fresh.

21:31.415 --> 21:34.376
He's on top of the rowle.
You gotta move him so I can get to it.

21:35.252 --> 21:38.005
No. Why don't you move him,
and I'll get the rowle?

21:38.505 --> 21:40.048
You don't even know what the rowle is.

21:42.050 --> 21:43.719
It's the round piece.

21:44.803 --> 21:46.804
Underneath the dead guy's arm.

21:46.805 --> 21:51.309
Yeah, see, I think I already did my part
by giving you that pep talk, you know,

21:51.310 --> 21:52.894
so I'll just be over here.

21:57.274 --> 21:58.774
I can do this.

21:58.775 --> 22:00.860
- Yeah, you can.
- I can fix the ship.

22:00.861 --> 22:01.778
You got it.

22:02.446 --> 22:04.363
I can fix the ship.

22:04.364 --> 22:07.241
I can do it. I can do it.

22:07.242 --> 22:08.201
You got it.

22:08.869 --> 22:09.745
Gah.

22:13.915 --> 22:17.461
Oh.

22:19.171 --> 22:20.130
It's intact.

22:34.269 --> 22:35.644
Not a corpse.

22:35.645 --> 22:37.355
Just a weird guy.

22:37.356 --> 22:40.316
I can handle a weird guy.
You get the rowle.

22:40.317 --> 22:42.277
Nice ship you came in on.

22:46.865 --> 22:48.742
We'll be taking it.

23:02.422 --> 23:04.424
You're pretty fast for a dead man.

23:09.638 --> 23:12.766
You're pretty skilled
for a man who only uses his legs.

23:17.062 --> 23:18.771
It's a style choice.

23:18.772 --> 23:21.400
Judging by your outfit,
you're unfamiliar with the concept.

23:36.581 --> 23:38.290
Gah!

23:38.291 --> 23:39.709
Sanji!

23:40.210 --> 23:41.503
Watch your step!

23:54.933 --> 23:56.893
He said "we're" taking your ship.

23:57.477 --> 23:59.479
So someone else is out there.

24:05.110 --> 24:06.903
Something wrong with your compass?

24:08.321 --> 24:09.948
- No.
- Good.

24:11.032 --> 24:14.911
We need to be able to sail out as soon
as I get this whale to open its mouth.

24:17.998 --> 24:18.915
What is that?

24:19.624 --> 24:21.168
Besides a waste of our rope.

24:23.879 --> 24:26.465
You said I couldn't get us out of here
with a sword, so…

24:31.303 --> 24:32.637
I made a big sword.

24:35.223 --> 24:36.057
What?

24:37.476 --> 24:39.351
When the rudder is fixed, I'll use this

24:39.352 --> 24:43.939
to poke that big punching bag looking
thing on the roof of his mouth.

24:43.940 --> 24:45.025
The uvula?

24:49.988 --> 24:51.156
So it's a girl whale.

24:53.325 --> 24:54.575
Whatever.

24:54.576 --> 24:57.578
Then, we will be puked to freedom.

24:57.579 --> 25:00.664
Then the dumbest plan ever concocted
was spoken aloud.

25:00.665 --> 25:03.293
Well, it's the only plan
we've got right now, so…

25:16.598 --> 25:18.475
Do you know where my compass went?

25:44.751 --> 25:47.254
Zoro, a little help here!

25:53.093 --> 25:54.094
Ha!

26:09.943 --> 26:12.946
Sorry, but I need your ship.

26:15.782 --> 26:16.950
Let her go.

26:22.122 --> 26:23.290
Hmm.

26:27.669 --> 26:28.837
Did I miss something?

26:36.886 --> 26:39.097
Hmm. Yeah.

26:40.807 --> 26:42.892
Hmm. A bit more.

26:44.477 --> 26:46.479
How long is this gonna take?

26:48.064 --> 26:49.065
I told you.

26:49.608 --> 26:53.527
We have to wait until Laboon resurfaces.

26:53.528 --> 26:55.196
When that happens,

26:55.739 --> 26:58.575
I need to get another sedative ready.

26:59.200 --> 27:05.874
We won't go anywhere near that whale
until we have got him to calm down.

27:06.374 --> 27:08.585
- How often do you medicate him?
- These days?

27:09.169 --> 27:10.794
Up to 20 a day.

27:10.795 --> 27:13.672
Stop him ramming his head
into the Red Line.

27:13.673 --> 27:17.217
Why does he hit his head like that?
Why do you take care of him?

27:17.218 --> 27:18.927
Is he your pet?

27:18.928 --> 27:20.513
Absolutely not.

27:21.014 --> 27:22.724
I'm not an animal person.

27:23.224 --> 27:25.434
Not really a people person either.

27:25.435 --> 27:29.939
All I ever wanted was to be left alone.

27:32.108 --> 27:34.986
That's why I moved to a lighthouse
in the middle of nowhere.

27:37.572 --> 27:38.823
Then why keep doing it?

27:41.743 --> 27:42.827
Because…

27:46.456 --> 27:48.333
I made a promise too.

27:54.547 --> 27:59.051
<i>Gather up all of the crew
It's time to ship out Binks' brew!</i>

27:59.052 --> 28:03.806
<i>The sea wind blows, to where who knows
The waves will be our guide</i>

28:03.807 --> 28:08.602
<i>All across the ocean's tide
Rays of sunshine far and wide</i>

28:08.603 --> 28:13.232
<i>Birds, they sing of cheerful things
In circles passing by</i>

28:13.233 --> 28:22.033
<i>Yo, ho! Yo, ho, ho, ho!</i>

28:22.659 --> 28:27.037
<i>Yo, ho! Yo, ho, ho, ho!</i>

28:27.038 --> 28:30.250
Yo, ho, ho, ho, ho, ho, ho, ho, ho!

28:32.293 --> 28:34.921
Well done for crossing Reverse Mountain.

28:36.631 --> 28:38.757
Welcome to the pirates' graveyard.

28:38.758 --> 28:41.344
Apologies for docking
while we repair our ship.

28:41.928 --> 28:43.930
I'm known in the West Blue
as Calico Yorki,

28:44.848 --> 28:47.057
Captain of the Rumbar Pirates.

28:47.058 --> 28:49.811
You're welcome to stay
while you repair your ship.

28:50.854 --> 28:52.772
But don't cause me any trouble.

28:53.898 --> 28:54.815
Laboon?

28:54.816 --> 28:56.693
- Hey, Laboon!
- There he is!

28:57.902 --> 29:00.195
I didn't know you had a whale with you.

29:00.196 --> 29:01.906
He'll scare away the fish.

29:04.659 --> 29:06.286
Well, perhaps we can make a deal.

29:07.245 --> 29:08.829
You share your dock with us,

29:08.830 --> 29:12.207
and we'll share
our music and our food with you.

29:12.208 --> 29:15.627
I hate your music,
and I have more than enough food.

29:15.628 --> 29:18.422
Then perhaps

29:18.423 --> 29:21.049
some of our booze? Hmm?

29:21.050 --> 29:22.719
Ah.

29:29.100 --> 29:31.978
How did you end up
with a whale on your crew anyway?

29:34.522 --> 29:37.275
He started following us
back in the West Blue.

29:38.026 --> 29:42.113
Poor thing must have strayed from his pod.
He was all alone in the open ocean.

29:43.782 --> 29:45.575
The crew started to get attached.

29:46.075 --> 29:49.370
Especially when they realized
how much little Laboon loves music.

29:52.707 --> 29:59.379
<i>Gather up all of the crew
It's time to ship out Binks' brew!</i>

29:59.380 --> 30:02.257
<i>Sing a song and play along</i>

30:02.258 --> 30:07.680
<i>For all the oceans wide</i>

30:11.142 --> 30:14.561
<i>After all is said and done</i>

30:14.562 --> 30:17.481
<i>You'll end up a skeleton</i>

30:17.482 --> 30:21.026
<i>So spread your tale
From dawn till dusk</i>

30:21.027 --> 30:26.366
<i>Upon these foamy seas!</i>

30:33.665 --> 30:37.377
I was surprised he survived
the journey over Reverse Mountain.

30:37.877 --> 30:40.964
Yeah. Yeah, he's a tough little thing.

30:41.965 --> 30:44.926
Not tough enough
for the Grand Line, I'll wager.

30:45.885 --> 30:49.513
Beasts waiting in the depths
to make an appetizer of him

30:49.514 --> 30:51.850
the moment you raise anchor.

30:57.355 --> 30:59.232
If Laboon finds himself in danger,

31:00.525 --> 31:03.444
every man on my ship
would sacrifice himself for him.

31:04.904 --> 31:07.322
Imagine making it to the Grand Line

31:07.323 --> 31:09.742
and losing it all for a whale.

31:11.494 --> 31:13.746
Taking on a vulnerable creature like that,

31:14.414 --> 31:17.292
letting him loose
in such dangerous waters.

31:20.503 --> 31:22.672
Glad it's not on my conscience.

31:33.641 --> 31:37.102
We cannot repay your kindness to us,
and to Laboon.

31:37.103 --> 31:41.024
I wouldn't have agreed to this
if I hadn't been six drinks deep.

31:42.191 --> 31:43.776
You're a good man, Crocus.

31:44.903 --> 31:46.571
I know you'll keep your word.

31:48.239 --> 31:49.365
Aye.

31:50.199 --> 31:53.327
We'll sail around the world
on the Grand Line

31:53.328 --> 31:56.456
and return right back here
from the other side of this mountain.

31:58.625 --> 32:01.044
I promise we'll be back
after our adventures.

32:01.836 --> 32:04.297
And we'll have so many more
when we reunite.

32:13.139 --> 32:15.265
<i>Gather up all of the crew</i>

32:15.266 --> 32:17.768
<i>It's time to ship out Binks' brew!</i>

32:17.769 --> 32:20.062
<i>Sea wind blows to where, who knows?</i>

32:20.063 --> 32:22.606
<i>The waves will be our guide</i>

32:22.607 --> 32:25.068
<i>All across the ocean's tide</i>

32:46.881 --> 32:48.841
I know the song they sang to Laboon.

32:49.467 --> 32:51.677
- "Binks' Brew."
- Mmm.

32:51.678 --> 32:53.096
Someone used to sing it to me.

32:54.639 --> 32:56.432
Someone who left a long time ago.

32:59.560 --> 33:02.772
Laboon's crew left,
but they never returned.

33:03.523 --> 33:07.527
I've even set out myself
to search for them.

33:08.111 --> 33:13.157
I found a reliable source who'd seen
their ship fleeing the Grand Line.

33:13.908 --> 33:16.869
He thinks they're sailing around
behind that wall,

33:17.412 --> 33:19.247
and if he hits it hard enough,

33:19.747 --> 33:21.791
he can break through to them.

33:24.627 --> 33:28.715
The Red Line is impenetrable.

33:29.799 --> 33:32.301
He'll keep bashing at it until he dies.

33:32.802 --> 33:36.681
I tried my best to get him to stop
when I told him what I'd learned.

33:37.181 --> 33:40.393
Laboon, you needed to know the truth.

33:40.893 --> 33:42.562
They're not coming back.

33:44.522 --> 33:46.691
They've left, Laboon.

33:47.650 --> 33:50.862
You need to give up
before you kill yourself.

33:56.701 --> 33:58.119
Stop it!

34:05.293 --> 34:07.003
<i>But it was no use.</i>

34:08.379 --> 34:12.925
Now I do all I can
to keep Laboon from hurting himself.

34:13.509 --> 34:16.471
But as soon as the sedative wears off,
he's back at it.

34:16.971 --> 34:20.058
He'll never accept
that his crew's not coming back.

34:25.688 --> 34:26.773
You're a good guy.

34:27.565 --> 34:29.191
Taking care of your friends.

34:29.192 --> 34:32.070
I'm no good at taking care of anyone.

34:32.695 --> 34:34.572
I'm just what he's stuck with.

34:36.199 --> 34:38.408
Calico Yorki was right to trust you.

34:38.409 --> 34:40.078
It doesn't matter.

34:41.913 --> 34:48.294
Laboon has been injected so many times,
the sedative is losing its effectiveness.

34:48.878 --> 34:50.963
And when it stops working altogeth…

34:53.091 --> 34:54.592
Hey. Hey. Hey.

34:55.676 --> 34:57.762
There's got to be
another way to help him out.

34:58.971 --> 35:01.724
To get him to accept his crew is gone.

35:03.059 --> 35:04.936
You wouldn't accept it.

35:15.863 --> 35:17.155
How's it looking?

35:17.156 --> 35:18.908
Whipstaff's back in working order.

35:19.408 --> 35:22.286
As soon as I untangle this knot,
she'll be seaworthy.

35:22.870 --> 35:24.038
Well, be careful.

35:24.664 --> 35:26.414
You don't have to worry about me.

35:26.415 --> 35:28.709
Whoa! Oh! Oh!

35:32.380 --> 35:34.590
I'm good. I'm good.

35:42.473 --> 35:43.724
All right, you two.

35:44.308 --> 35:46.852
Give us answers
or I start cutting things off.

35:46.853 --> 35:47.728
Why are you here?

35:49.147 --> 35:51.941
There are many reasons
a person ends up inside a whale.

35:52.441 --> 35:53.483
Why are <i>you</i> here?

35:53.484 --> 35:55.069
Why did you want to take our ship?

35:56.154 --> 35:58.321
One can't just walk out of a whale.

35:58.322 --> 35:59.948
You should untie us now

35:59.949 --> 36:02.117
or forfeit your lives.

36:02.118 --> 36:04.536
You think we're afraid
of two unarmed people

36:04.537 --> 36:06.789
dressed like they do
bad community theater, yeah?

36:07.290 --> 36:11.042
We are much, much more
than you could ever imagine.

36:11.043 --> 36:12.044
"We"?

36:13.045 --> 36:14.755
Ridiculous costumes.

36:15.256 --> 36:17.175
Unfounded overconfidence.

36:18.176 --> 36:19.927
I've faced their kind before.

36:22.930 --> 36:25.975
Some guy who called himself… Mr. 7.

36:28.728 --> 36:30.188
Hey! Easy, mosshead.

36:39.197 --> 36:40.656
I guess that makes you

36:41.741 --> 36:42.909
Mr. 9?

36:43.743 --> 36:45.995
So our reputation precedes us.

36:46.996 --> 36:48.121
Who are they?

36:48.122 --> 36:49.999
<i>They are Baroque Works.</i>

36:51.876 --> 36:54.837
For a long time,
the Marines have been on their trail,

36:55.421 --> 37:00.550
hunting down any trace
of this… mysterious menace.

37:00.551 --> 37:05.765
An organization with tendrils extending
from the Grand Line to every other sea.

37:08.184 --> 37:09.560
At first, they were

37:10.770 --> 37:12.229
merely a rumor.

37:12.230 --> 37:15.690
A dark whisper.
But now they're growing bold.

37:15.691 --> 37:20.695
Shells Town is only the latest
Marine outpost they've decimated.

37:20.696 --> 37:22.240
What is their objective?

37:24.659 --> 37:25.618
Unknown.

37:26.494 --> 37:29.497
We've never managed
to capture one of their operatives.

37:29.997 --> 37:31.457
Well, not alive anyway.

37:32.583 --> 37:35.628
They use code names

37:37.213 --> 37:39.381
to keep their identities a mystery.

37:39.382 --> 37:42.426
The true identity of their leader, Mr. 0,

37:42.927 --> 37:44.345
is unknown.

37:45.263 --> 37:48.849
Even in the highest rankings
of the organization itself.

37:52.436 --> 37:54.939
I told you to wait
with the other kids, Petty Officer.

38:01.070 --> 38:03.238
Stop saluting and get out.

38:03.239 --> 38:04.282
Yes, sir.

38:09.495 --> 38:11.913
I will allow you
to transfer to the Grand Line.

38:11.914 --> 38:15.166
- I wasn't asking permission--
- But your mission is this.

38:15.167 --> 38:18.920
Capture a Baroque Works agent alive.

38:18.921 --> 38:23.718
Gather intelligence from them
before any other island ends up like this.

38:24.385 --> 38:26.554
- Why me?
- You're focused.

38:27.138 --> 38:28.431
Ruthless.

38:29.181 --> 38:31.100
And you'll do whatever it takes.

38:32.143 --> 38:33.894
That jitte you carry,

38:35.354 --> 38:37.898
the tip of it
is made of seastone, isn't it?

38:39.483 --> 38:40.401
Yes, sir.

38:40.985 --> 38:41.902
That,

38:43.070 --> 38:44.613
and your other powers,

38:45.323 --> 38:48.408
should give you an enviable advantage.

38:48.409 --> 38:51.454
That's why I need you on this.

38:52.371 --> 38:53.914
But try to keep in mind,

38:55.541 --> 38:57.752
there's a bigger picture here.

38:59.211 --> 39:01.629
<i>They're an organization of assassins.</i>

39:01.630 --> 39:04.884
They sent their Mr. 7
to try to recruit me a while back.

39:05.468 --> 39:06.761
Assuming you said no?

39:07.845 --> 39:09.513
I was a bit more cutting than that.

39:11.849 --> 39:12.975
I cut him in half.

39:13.642 --> 39:15.144
Yeah. No, we got it.

39:16.312 --> 39:19.064
Well, look, they don't seem too dangerous.

39:19.065 --> 39:20.565
I mean, you killed 7.

39:20.566 --> 39:23.818
9 basically took himself out of our fight
by dropping down a hole, so--

39:23.819 --> 39:27.740
I've been in this whale for days.
I'm not at full strength.

39:28.240 --> 39:29.992
Tell them, Miss Wednesday.

39:31.452 --> 39:33.662
Numbers and days for code names.

39:34.163 --> 39:35.373
Clever.

39:45.383 --> 39:47.885
I say we deal with them
the old-fashioned way.

39:49.303 --> 39:50.345
Throw them overboard.

39:50.346 --> 39:52.680
I don't think
our captain would want us killing.

39:52.681 --> 39:55.225
Our captain isn't here right now, is he?

39:55.226 --> 39:56.727
Oh.

39:57.228 --> 39:58.729
Let me guess.

39:59.271 --> 40:01.689
You're the navigator
that got all your friends stuck in this.

40:01.690 --> 40:04.526
And you're the thief
that stole my compass. Where is it?

40:04.527 --> 40:05.860
Went for a swim.

40:05.861 --> 40:07.070
I needed that.

40:07.071 --> 40:09.532
Doesn't seem like it was
doing you much good.

40:11.826 --> 40:13.786
You don't need it
in the Grand Line anyway.

40:14.370 --> 40:16.621
Magnetic fields are
completely different here.

40:16.622 --> 40:18.249
Only works with a Log Pose.

40:20.960 --> 40:23.503
You… you do have a Log Pose?

40:23.504 --> 40:25.381
Uh, yeah, of course we do.

40:26.298 --> 40:27.383
What's a Log Pose?

40:31.178 --> 40:33.722
Of all the whales in all the world,

40:34.223 --> 40:36.600
this crack team had to wander into mine.

40:37.143 --> 40:38.601
We're never getting out of here.

40:38.602 --> 40:41.646
At least we kept our ship intact.
You two clearly didn't.

40:41.647 --> 40:44.650
A crew is only as good as its navigator.

40:45.234 --> 40:46.777
You're all as good as dead.

40:47.278 --> 40:50.322
Do you have any idea where you are?

40:52.825 --> 40:54.743
Grab onto something fast.

40:56.829 --> 40:59.373
Usopp!

41:02.293 --> 41:04.837
Oh, oh, oh. Oh! Oh.

41:10.551 --> 41:12.635
Usopp! Usopp!

41:12.636 --> 41:13.845
Just stay calm.

41:13.846 --> 41:16.599
I will not! Aah!

41:27.693 --> 41:30.278
Damn, he woke up early.

41:30.279 --> 41:31.322
Come on.

41:35.910 --> 41:38.745
- What's happening to my crew in there?
- Nothing good.

41:38.746 --> 41:39.872
Usopp!

41:44.752 --> 41:46.462
Hurry up, Pops.

42:04.063 --> 42:05.313
It's not working.

42:05.314 --> 42:07.733
Damn. I should have upped the dosage.

42:08.734 --> 42:10.069
I need to get closer.

42:10.653 --> 42:11.570
That's crazy.

42:16.283 --> 42:17.535
You'll die.

42:18.118 --> 42:19.745
I don't care.

42:36.303 --> 42:38.264
We need something for him to grab onto!

42:41.976 --> 42:42.977
Here.

42:44.061 --> 42:45.729
What the hell is that?

42:47.106 --> 42:48.524
No!

42:49.108 --> 42:50.316
Aah!

42:50.317 --> 42:52.403
Wow, can't believe that didn't work.

42:56.490 --> 42:58.075
Hey, whale!

42:58.951 --> 43:01.453
Don't you dare hurt my friends!

43:05.082 --> 43:09.211
You don't get to eat my crew!

43:18.679 --> 43:19.637
Oh!

43:19.638 --> 43:21.181
Oh dear.

43:39.658 --> 43:41.368
Don't let me go!

43:43.454 --> 43:44.913
Pull me up!

43:49.668 --> 43:51.086
Zoro, hold on.

43:51.754 --> 43:54.756
It's slippery!

43:54.757 --> 43:56.592
Sanji, don't let me go!

43:57.343 --> 43:58.344
Aah!

44:00.012 --> 44:01.013
Got you.

44:03.349 --> 44:04.766
Pull on three.

44:04.767 --> 44:08.145
One, two, three!

44:41.637 --> 44:47.559
<i>Yo, ho, ho, ho! Yo, ho, ho, ho!</i>

44:48.519 --> 44:53.399
<i>Yo, ho, ho, ho! Yo, ho, ho, ho!</i>

44:55.025 --> 45:00.988
<i>Gather up all of the crew
It's time to ship out Binks' brew!</i>

45:00.989 --> 45:06.160
<i>Wave goodbye, but don't you cry
Our memories remain</i>

45:06.161 --> 45:11.249
<i>Our days are but a passing dream
Everlasting though they seem</i>

45:11.250 --> 45:15.503
<i>Beneath the moon we'll meet again
The wind's our lullaby</i>

45:15.504 --> 45:20.591
<i>We gather up all of the crew
It's time to ship out Binks' brew!</i>

45:20.592 --> 45:24.637
<i>Wave goodbye, but don't you cry
Our memories remain</i>

45:24.638 --> 45:29.350
<i>Our days are but a passing dream
Everlasting though they seem</i>

45:29.351 --> 45:36.358
<i>Beneath the moon we'll meet again
The wind's our lullaby!</i>

45:50.080 --> 45:52.332
People leave, Laboon.

45:54.251 --> 45:55.669
But sometimes,

45:56.170 --> 45:59.214
you end up somewhere
you never thought you would.

46:00.674 --> 46:02.760
And you meet people who stay.

46:16.440 --> 46:20.152
I need my friends, Laboon.

46:21.695 --> 46:22.821
Please,

46:24.198 --> 46:25.407
let them go.

46:40.380 --> 46:41.632
Zoro,

46:42.674 --> 46:43.842
set the main!

46:45.677 --> 46:47.471
Let's turn this ship around.

47:23.173 --> 47:26.927
Well, I'll be damned.

47:28.428 --> 47:30.264
Guys!

47:30.848 --> 47:31.889
Guys!

47:31.890 --> 47:33.016
Luffy!

47:40.649 --> 47:42.109
Whoo!

47:46.697 --> 47:48.240
Told you, Pops!

47:57.499 --> 48:01.420
Must you always
show me up in everything? Huh?

48:07.885 --> 48:08.719
Caught spying?

48:11.013 --> 48:12.139
How'd you know?

48:14.099 --> 48:16.309
Eavesdropped from behind a few doors
in my day.

48:16.310 --> 48:19.771
He's basically an expert in espionage.

48:22.441 --> 48:23.609
Do you want a turn?

48:24.526 --> 48:26.986
Swords are more my weapon of choice.

48:26.987 --> 48:28.029
Relatable.

48:28.030 --> 48:30.198
I love swords. That's why I…

48:31.992 --> 48:33.242
Never mind.

48:33.243 --> 48:37.205
Captain Smoker's warned me
against talking about my dreams too much.

48:38.165 --> 48:39.791
And talking in general.

48:40.584 --> 48:42.502
That's why you wanted to become a Marine?

48:44.546 --> 48:45.796
To train in swords?

48:45.797 --> 48:47.465
Not just train.

48:47.466 --> 48:49.718
You know, swords sing to me.

48:50.218 --> 48:51.219
They always have.

48:51.720 --> 48:54.972
I found out that there's this collection
of masterwork blades.

48:54.973 --> 48:56.725
Each one has their own name.

48:57.225 --> 49:00.729
Most are in the hands of pirates
and bounty hunters now.

49:01.563 --> 49:04.023
But if I could, I would hunt down
every one of those swords

49:04.024 --> 49:06.902
and take them away
from the bad men that don't deserve them.

49:07.402 --> 49:09.780
I'm assuming Captain Smoker isn't the most

49:10.656 --> 49:12.407
supportive of that mission?

49:13.533 --> 49:14.534
I don't make the orders.

49:18.497 --> 49:20.791
I became a Marine
because I had a dream too.

49:22.292 --> 49:24.753
Getting justice for anyone
that's ever been stepped on.

49:26.004 --> 49:27.297
'Cause I know what that's like.

49:29.424 --> 49:32.803
Garp teaches us that following orders
doesn't make you a good Marine.

49:33.804 --> 49:35.180
It's following your code.

49:36.223 --> 49:37.808
Your own brand of justice.

49:41.812 --> 49:43.981
Sounds like the Vice Admiral's
a great teacher.

49:44.606 --> 49:46.191
Physical abuse aside.

49:50.737 --> 49:53.073
Only you can define the path for yourself.

50:04.501 --> 50:05.627
I fixed the door.

50:09.548 --> 50:12.134
You know, if you ever get sick
of living in a lighthouse,

50:12.759 --> 50:14.469
there's a lot of room inside Laboon.

50:14.970 --> 50:16.013
Thanks, buddy.

50:16.763 --> 50:19.725
You could build a whole house in there.
Live pretty comfortably.

50:21.435 --> 50:23.270
How cool would that be?

50:23.937 --> 50:25.439
To live inside a whale?

50:25.939 --> 50:29.901
If things ever truly go to shit,
I'll keep it in mind.

50:31.528 --> 50:34.030
What do we do with our friends
tied up onboard?

50:34.031 --> 50:37.868
I'd prefer if you didn't
leave two assassins on my little oasis.

50:38.368 --> 50:40.495
And the lady did help save Usopp.

50:40.996 --> 50:41.996
She did?

50:41.997 --> 50:44.541
- I still don't trust them.
- Nor should you.

50:45.333 --> 50:46.334
Mmm.

50:46.918 --> 50:49.712
Yeah, we'll, um, take them
to the next island with us

50:49.713 --> 50:52.424
and figure out what to do with them there.

50:54.593 --> 50:56.094
If we can get to the next island.

50:56.762 --> 50:58.095
Look, I have to be honest.

50:58.096 --> 51:02.059
I don't think I really anticipated just
how different things were gonna be here.

51:03.477 --> 51:06.937
I don't have the right skills.
I don't have the right tools.

51:06.938 --> 51:07.898
I…

51:08.398 --> 51:10.399
I don't even know what a Log Pose is.

51:10.400 --> 51:14.988
How am I supposed to navigate you
when I don't even know where I'm going?

51:17.574 --> 51:18.950
I'm so out of my element.

51:20.077 --> 51:23.497
Out of our element
is when this crew does its best work.

51:26.500 --> 51:28.502
A Log Pose is pretty simple.

51:29.920 --> 51:32.838
It measures
the magnetic field between islands.

51:32.839 --> 51:35.841
After reaching an island
and spending some time there,

51:35.842 --> 51:38.261
the Log Pose resets,

51:38.887 --> 51:40.180
locks onto a new island.

51:41.765 --> 51:43.307
Okay, that sounds easy.

51:43.308 --> 51:45.059
Here on Twin Capes,

51:45.060 --> 51:50.231
it locks onto an island from
one of seven possible magnetic fields,

51:50.232 --> 51:53.026
so even two ships
that leave the same place

51:53.527 --> 51:56.238
might not follow the same course.

51:57.531 --> 51:59.199
That sounds less easy.

52:00.617 --> 52:05.163
I've got an old one lying about somewhere.
I'd be happy to show you how it works.

52:06.248 --> 52:08.208
And give it to you for your journey.

52:08.959 --> 52:10.043
Really?

52:10.836 --> 52:13.337
My adventuring days are over.

52:13.338 --> 52:15.507
Long gone. And…

52:17.259 --> 52:19.845
I think you're the right person
to have it.

52:23.974 --> 52:26.560
Some of the best navigators in the world

52:27.727 --> 52:30.647
couldn't get as far
as you've come already.

52:34.860 --> 52:36.695
Couldn't have done it without my crew.

52:45.954 --> 52:47.872
- Hey, Flower Pops.
- Hmm?

52:47.873 --> 52:49.166
You got some paint?

53:00.427 --> 53:01.303
Done!

53:04.222 --> 53:06.016
All right, listen up, Laboon.

53:06.808 --> 53:08.517
That Jolly Roger right there,

53:08.518 --> 53:11.313
it's a symbol of your friendship
with the Straw Hats.

53:12.731 --> 53:16.610
So don't you ever hit your head
against that wall again, huh?

53:17.110 --> 53:18.278
I mean it.

53:19.321 --> 53:20.614
Or you'll make it disappear.

53:23.867 --> 53:26.369
I get why you're waiting for your friends.

53:29.206 --> 53:30.916
It's because you believe in them.

53:34.544 --> 53:38.131
Well, you're one of us now, Laboon.

53:38.632 --> 53:40.258
We'll come back to you.

53:43.220 --> 53:44.512
That's a promise.

53:58.610 --> 53:59.569
Tashigi.

54:02.322 --> 54:05.033
Master Chief Petty Officer Tashigi.

54:08.328 --> 54:10.079
I'm heading to the Grand Line.

54:10.080 --> 54:12.123
I need you to stay here
and keep watch over Loguetown.

54:12.707 --> 54:14.167
Await further instruction.

54:16.544 --> 54:17.921
Is that understood?

54:19.965 --> 54:20.966
No.

54:21.675 --> 54:22.800
Excuse me?

54:22.801 --> 54:23.968
I'm going with you.

54:23.969 --> 54:26.136
I have a Gold Roger of my own
to hunt down,

54:26.137 --> 54:28.306
and I'm going to capture him
with my own hands.

54:28.807 --> 54:31.977
And anyone else
unworthy of a sword in their possession.

54:33.228 --> 54:34.813
What the hell are you talking about?

54:35.814 --> 54:39.359
At some point, I have to stop
following orders and follow my own code.

54:40.193 --> 54:41.569
That day is today.

54:42.654 --> 54:44.571
Surely that's something you understand.

54:44.572 --> 54:46.532
Tashigi, you saw the footage back there.

54:46.533 --> 54:48.994
You know what Baroque Works is capable of.

54:50.161 --> 54:52.580
You really want to get mixed up in that
for a sword?

54:53.873 --> 54:55.375
For many swords.

54:56.459 --> 54:57.335
And yes.

55:05.343 --> 55:06.177
Well,

55:07.387 --> 55:08.470
your funeral.

55:08.471 --> 55:09.431
Let's go.

55:12.809 --> 55:15.687
And don't do a little dance.

55:33.580 --> 55:36.583
Are you ready to chart
your very first island in the Grand Line?

55:37.083 --> 55:40.753
Twin Capes! You'll have to help me
with the layout of Crocus's lighthouse.

55:40.754 --> 55:43.506
Bringing some food
back to my friends on the brig.

55:44.007 --> 55:46.091
Nobody goes hungry on this ship.

55:46.092 --> 55:47.635
Very thoughtful.

55:49.220 --> 55:53.350
What are the chances that the people on
the next island are as friendly as Crocus?

55:54.517 --> 55:56.102
And as free with the booze?

55:57.187 --> 55:59.271
No way to know what's coming next.

55:59.272 --> 56:02.942
But that's part of the fun, I guess.

56:06.112 --> 56:10.367
So, what do you think, Roger?

56:11.117 --> 56:13.870
Perhaps he's the one
we've been waiting for.

56:14.621 --> 56:17.623
The one who will make it to Laugh Tale

56:17.624 --> 56:20.085
and find the One Piece.

56:20.877 --> 56:21.836
Hmm.

56:32.097 --> 56:33.430
Luffy?

56:33.431 --> 56:34.474
Hmm?

56:34.974 --> 56:36.768
Next island is straight ahead.
